<subSubSection pageId="160" pageNumber="161" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="160" pageNumber="161">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="160" pageNumber="161">
Endemic to southeastern Iran (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="160" pageNumber="161">Popov</emphasis>
51/157, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="160" pageNumber="161">Rechinger</emphasis>
55064, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="160" pageNumber="161">Mirzayan</emphasis>
830E, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="160" pageNumber="161">Assadi in Rechinger</emphasis>
54802, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="160" pageNumber="161">Runemark et al.</emphasis>
22616).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="160" pageNumber="161" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="160" pageNumber="161">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="160" pageNumber="161">
Superficially similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boiss. Diagn. Pl. Orient 7: 23. 1846. (Boissier" authorityYear="1846" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus oxysepalus" order="Solanales" pageId="160" pageNumber="161" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oxysepalus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="160" pageNumber="161">Convolvulus oxysepalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but the stem and leaves greyish-sericeous with adpressed hairs, the plant more obviously spiny with short-lateral spinescent branchlets in addition to the spinescent main shoots; the ovary is densely pilose and the style thinly pubescent, the stigmas only 3 mm long.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
